ethics and war restrepo film events at stanford ethics and war restrepo film facebook twitter email print add to calendar restrepo is a feature length documentary that chronicles the deployment of a platoon of us soldiers in afghanistan's korengal valley the movie focuses on a remote 15 man outpost restrepo named after a platoon medic who was killed in action it was considered one of the most dangerous postings in the us military this is an entirely experiential film the cameras never leave the valley there are no interviews with generals or diplomats the only goal is to make viewers feel as if they have just been through a 90 minute deployment the film was creaetd by sebastian junger and tim hetherington both of whom were embedded with battle company of the 173rd airborne brigade combat team in the remote and heavily contested korengal valley of eastern afghanistan reporting on the war from the soldiers perspective they spent weeks at a time at a remote outpost that saw more combat than almost anywhere else in the entire country following the screening junger will be in conversation with kristine samuelson art and art history on february 21 junger is in conversation with tobias wolff english when wednesday february 22 2012 7 00 pm approximate duration of 2 hour s where cemex auditorium zambrano hall knight management center stanford ca 94305 usa map audience general public faculty staff students alumni friends tags arts lecture reading international humanities film sponsor center for ethics in society creative writing program contact 650 723 0011 krystalg stanford edu admission free and open to the public but seating is limited stanford faculty please contact krystal griffiths at krystalg stanford edu if you plan to bring your class to this event permalink http events stanford edu events 310 31025 more info last modified february 10 2012
